```json
{
  "title": "See You After Snack Time",
  "pages": [
    {
      "pageNumber": 1,
      "text": "Every morning, Bear rode to nursery on his dad's back. He could smell his dad's jacket — coffee and cold outside air — and feel his dad's hands holding his ankles. Warm and sure."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 2,
      "text": "The nursery room smelled like crayons and damp clay. There was a window seat that looked out at the garden. Bear mostly liked it there. But the room felt biggest and brightest when his dad was still in it."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 3,
      "text": "His dad knelt down. He looked right at Bear. \"See you after snack time, okay? I'll be right at the gate.\" He reached into Bear's pocket and tapped the smooth grey stone inside. Then he stood up."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 4,
      "text": "Bear watched his dad's back. He watched him walk to the door. The door closed. Bear's hands went into his pockets. The room felt louder than before."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 5,
      "text": "Later, Bear sat at the clay table. His hands slowed down. Then they stopped. His throat felt like something was stuck in it. His legs felt heavy. He went very still and very quiet."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 6,
      "text": "His teacher sat nearby. She didn't try to fix anything. She just said, quietly, \"Your body knows he's not here yet. That's what missing feels like — it sits in your chest and waits with you.\" Bear didn't answer. But his shoulders moved down, just a little."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 7,
      "text": "His fingers found the stone on their own. He hadn't decided to. They just went there. The stone was smooth and cool and exactly the weight it always was. He held it, and he could almost feel his dad's hand over his, the two of them standing at the river, water running fast over the rocks."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 8,
      "text": "The heavy feeling didn't go away. But the room got a little less loud. Bear picked up the clay again."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 9,
      "text": "Then snack time came. The same cups. The same crackers. The same window. It came just the way it always did. Bear looked at the cups. He looked at the crackers. The world had done what it said it would do."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 10,
      "text": "Bear looked out the window. And there, at the gate, was his dad. Coat on. Exactly where he said he would be. Their eyes met through the glass."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 11,
      "text": "Bear stood still for one breath. Just one. Long enough to know: the goodbye had ended. Then he ran."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 12,
      "text": "His dad caught him. Bear pressed his face into the coffee-and-outside-air smell of his dad's jacket. The stone was still in his pocket. It felt warmer now."
    }
  ]
}
